!front: When solving an inequality $a \le b$, what happens with the inequality direction if we multiply both sides by a positive constant $c$?
!back: Inequality direction stays the same.
~~~

!id: 1b938e34-fd9e-4622-9df5-7aabeafa0715
!front: When solving an inequality $a \le b$, what happens with the inequality direction if we multiply both sides by a negative constant $c$?
!back: Inequality direction flips.
~~~

!id: 7e89c3c4-e6c6-4460-a316-c6ff7c2645a2
!front: If $a \le b$ and $f$ is an increasing function, what happens to the inequality after applying $f$?
!back:
It stays the same:

\[ f(a) \le f(b) \]
~~~

!id: cb4c9e76-d9f0-46e2-a120-27e4fcba884f
!front: If $a \le b$ and $f$ is a decreasing function, what happens to the inequality after applying $f$?
!back:
The direction flips:

\[ f(a) \ge f(b) \]
~~~

!id: c4d0fd29-cd7a-4032-a8bb-a3d01e1b0bb1
!front: If $0 < a \le b$, what inequality holds between $1/a$ and $1/b$?
!back: $1/a \ge 1/b$ (reciprocal is decreasing for positive numbers).
~~~

!id: f3adbad3-e71a-4663-b894-81d377ade0b6
!front: Is it true that if $a > b$ then $\ln(a) > \ln(b)$? Why?
!back:
Yes, if $a > 0$ and $b > 0$ then

\[ a > b \implies \ln(a) > \ln(b) \]

because $\ln(x)$ is monotonic and strictly increasing.
~~~

!id: d259786e-b15b-40bf-b710-bf90f0d7d8fe
!front: Is it true that if $a > b$ then $e^a > e^b$? Why?
!back:
Yes, for any $a$ and $b$

\[ a > b \implies e^a > e^b \]

because $\ln(x)$ is monotonic and strictly increasing.
~~~

